{"id":"aba-zca.3","title":"Phase 1: Pluggable Scanner Architecture","description":"## What

Design and implement the pluggable Scanner interface that all scanner implementations will use. This defines the contract for how scanners discover, parse, and produce graph nodes from source code. Includes a scanner registry and shared utilities.

## Context

The user explicitly chose pluggable architecture over purpose-built scanners. This means:
- A Scanner interface that new scanners can implement
- A registry that discovers and runs configured scanners
- Shared AST parsing utilities
- Configuration-driven scanner selection

Each scanner is responsible for:
1. Reading source files from configured paths
2. Parsing them into graph nodes (with properties)
3. Computing scan hashes for change detection
4. Returning nodes + edges for the graph layer to persist

Scanners should be stateless — they receive config, read files, and return results. The caller (scan command) handles persistence.

## Implementation

### Scanner Interface (packages/core/src/scanner/types.ts)

\`\`\`typescript
import type { GraphNode, GraphEdge, NodeKind } from '../types.js';

export interface ScannerConfig {
  /** Unique scanner identifier */
  id: string;
  /** Whether this scanner is enabled */
  enabled: boolean;
  /** Scanner-specific configuration */
  options: Record<string, unknown>;
}

export interface ScanResult {
  /** Nodes discovered by this scanner */
  nodes: Omit<GraphNode, 'created_at' | 'updated_at'>[];
  /** Edges between discovered nodes */
  edges: Omit<GraphEdge, 'created_at'>[];
  /** Warnings (non-fatal issues during scanning) */
  warnings: ScanWarning[];
  /** Summary statistics */
  stats: {
    filesScanned: number;
    nodesFound: number;
    edgesFound: number;
    errors: number;
  };
}

export interface ScanWarning {
  file: string;
  line?: number;
  message: string;
  severity: 'info' | 'warn' | 'error';
}

export interface Scanner {
  /** Unique identifier for this scanner */
  readonly id: string;
  /** Human-readable name */
  readonly name: string;
  /** What node kind(s) this scanner produces */
  readonly produces: NodeKind[];
  /** Validate configuration before scanning */
  validateConfig(config: ScannerConfig): { valid: boolean; errors: string[] };
  /** Execute the scan against the target project */
  scan(projectRoot: string, config: ScannerConfig): Promise<ScanResult>;
}
\`\`\`

### Scanner Registry (packages/core/src/scanner/registry.ts)

\`\`\`typescript
export class ScannerRegistry {
  private scanners = new Map<string, Scanner>();

  /** Register a scanner implementation */
  register(scanner: Scanner): void;

  /** Get a scanner by ID */
  get(id: string): Scanner | undefined;

  /** List all registered scanners */
  list(): Scanner[];

  /** Run all enabled scanners and merge results */
  async runAll(projectRoot: string, configs: ScannerConfig[]): Promise<MergedScanResult>;
}
\`\`\`

### Shared Utilities (packages/core/src/scanner/utils.ts)

- \`computeScanHash(content: string): string\` — SHA-256 hash for change detection
- \`resolveGlobs(projectRoot: string, patterns: string[]): string[]\` — resolve file globs relative to project root
- \`generateNodeId(kind: NodeKind, ...parts: string[]): string\` — deterministic ID generation
- \`parseConfig(configPath: string): AbacusConfig\` — read and validate .abacus/config.yaml

### Default Scanner Registration

The registry should auto-register the three built-in scanners (oRPC, Prisma, Router) when created. External scanners can be registered via plugins in the future.

## Testing

- [ ] Scanner interface is correctly typed — implementing a mock scanner compiles
- [ ] ScannerRegistry.register() stores scanner and retrieves by ID
- [ ] ScannerRegistry.runAll() calls each enabled scanner and merges results
- [ ] ScannerRegistry.runAll() skips disabled scanners
- [ ] ScannerRegistry.runAll() continues on scanner error, reports in warnings
- [ ] computeScanHash produces deterministic hashes for identical content
- [ ] computeScanHash produces different hashes for different content
- [ ] resolveGlobs correctly expands glob patterns relative to project root
- [ ] generateNodeId produces deterministic IDs (same inputs → same ID)
- [ ] parseConfig reads valid YAML and returns typed config
- [ ] parseConfig throws descriptive error for invalid YAML
- [ ] validateConfig catches missing required fields

## Validation

- [ ] A test scanner implementing the Scanner interface can be registered and run
- [ ] Multiple scanners can run concurrently without interference
- [ ] Scan results merge correctly (no duplicate node IDs across scanners)
- [ ] Error in one scanner doesn't crash the scan pipeline

## Files

- packages/core/src/scanner/types.ts
- packages/core/src/scanner/registry.ts
- packages/core/src/scanner/utils.ts
- packages/core/src/scanner/index.ts (re-exports)
- packages/core/src/__tests__/scanner/registry.test.ts
- packages/core/src/__tests__/scanner/utils.test.ts

## Dependencies

